Mapping the American Golden Plover (Pluvialis dominica) migration

The American Golden Plover? Why should I care about a grey little bird?

Well first of all, it's actually grey-brown. I first learned about the American golden plover from the movie The Big Year, a commedy about three birders competing to see who can observe the move birds in one calendar year. Jack Black's character (Brad Harris) is talking to his dad about his favorite bird, the American golden plover. Click here for the video or read the transcript below!

Brad Harris: There's my favorite bird. American golden plover.

Raymond Harris (Brad's Dad who doesn't like birds): That's your favorite bird? It's gray.

Brad: Yes, it is. Well, gray-brown. Yeah, a lot of people wouldn't think twice to look at this bird, but this golden plover's one of the greatest travelers in the world. It's true. It breeds in the Arctic tundra, then flies all the way down to Argentina and back, all in one year. It shows up on beaches of Guatemala. On farms in Illinois. Nine inches long, but he travels hundreds of thousands of miles in his lifetime. No passports, no security. Total freedom. Yeah. This gray bird has seen some amazing things. And that's the bird that everybody underestimates.

It's true! The American golden plover does have one of the longest migratory routes of any bird species at ~24,000 km (~15,000 miles) (1). Golden plovers breed in the tundra of North American and then overwinter in southern South America. Their southern migration route even contains a 3000-5000 km stretch of flight that is entirely over the Atlantic Ocean, meaning these birds cannot stop to rest or feed during this time (2). See the figure below from The Migration of North American Birds published in 1935 by Frederick C. Lincoln of the USDA.

Existing American golden plover range maps

I wanted to compare the American golden plover migration routes recorded by sources like Birds of the World (Cornell University) and Brad Harris (Jack Black) with occurrence records published on the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF). One important note, the migratory maps from Birds of the World (shown below) are based on actual radar tracking data, such as Lamarre et al., 2021. Observational occurrence data could be a useful, cost-effective supplement to this data, but we can't draw conclusions about how far individual birds are traveling in a given year.

Question: Do the migration routes between Birds of the World, Brad Harris, and GBIF agree?

Prediction: Because Brad Harris is a good guy and great birder (no spoilers watch the movie), and Cornell is a notable birding institution, I posit that the migration routes between these sources will agree. Supplementing this data with GBIF occurrence data should inflate the range of of the American golden plover migration compared to Birds of the World and Brad Harris. I think this will offer a less conservative view of these birds range, in-part due to not being reliant on GPS tracking and having more data points, and due to possible mis-identification of similar species.

Workflow for visualizing the migration patterns of the American golden plover

Step 0: Import necessary Python libraries

Step 1: Download World Wildlife Fund Ecoregions

Step 2: Load in pre-downloaded GBIF data for the American golden plover

  • Downloaded data using gbif-data-downlaod.ipynb

Step 3: Spatially join WWF ecoregions and GBIF observations

Step 4: Normalize GBIF occurence data

  • Calculate per month occurrence in each ecoregion occurrence
  • Calculate observation density (# observations per month / ecoregion area)
  • Remove occurences < 1 (rare, possible misidentifications)
  • Calculate per ecoregion mean occurrence density
  • Calculate per month occurrence density
  • Normalized occurrence = density / mean_mont_density / mean_ecoregion_density

Step 5: Visualize normalized density in each ecoregion for each month

  • This will show us the normalized densities of American golden plovers for each ecoregion throughout their migration.

Step 4: Normalize observation data

In[8]:
# Raw occurrence data
occurrence_df = (
    gbif_ecoregion_gdf
    # Reset index
    .reset_index()
    # For each ecoregion, for each month...
    # note that OBJECTID corresponds to the ecoregion
    .groupby(['ecoregion_id', 'month'])
    # ...count the number of occurrences
    .agg(occurrences=('gbifID', 'count'),
         area=('area', 'first'))
)

# Normalize by area
occurrence_df['density'] = (
    occurrence_df.occurrences
    / occurrence_df.area
)

Conclusion: How does the GBIF migration map compare to the World of Birds and Brad Harris migration?
Here is that map from Birds of the World again:



Birds of the World and Brad: We can see clearly that Brad Harris and Birds of the World are on the same page. The map shows that the American golden plover spends it's non-breeding overwintering time in northern Argentina, and migrates through both Guatemala and Illinois on it's way to breed in the tundra.


How does our map agree? Our map broadly agrees! We see winter (Dec - Feb) plover observations concentrated in southern South America. Migrating birds reach the Tundra by May and don't leave until August. Their overflight takes them through Guatemala and Illinois. Notably, this timing agrees with other published timings of American golden plover migration. For example, a conservation plan by Clay et al., 2010 notes that plovers start migrating south from their breeding habitat in late June to mid-July (these are failed breeders), with the majority of the adults leaving in August. They also note that August is the first month where birds arrive on non-breeding grounds, which also agrees with our map. There is also agreement with literature on the birds northern migration. Clay et al state that birds start leaving non-breeding ground in late January, with most leaving in February. Some birds even stick around in South American until April and May, which our map also shows. April is major influx of birds in the Missouri, Mississippi, and Ohio River valleys. Plovers arrive on breeding grounds starting in mind-May to early June, which our maps clearly show.


How does our map disagree? Our map is possibly overestimating the range of the American golden plover. You can see that the overwinter observations of the plover (see January) extend all the way to the southern tip of South America. It is certainly possible that some birds migrate this far south, but our map might be affected in part by the size of the ecoregions we're using to bin occurrences. For example, if a bird was spotten in the northern area of the one of the southern-Argentinian ecoregions, the entire ecoregion will be filled. The same pattern can be seen in the Artic tundra ecoregions. Finer spatial resolution binning could improve this.


Something cool to note: There is a small population of American golden plovers in Europe. While some of these might be misidentifications of European golden plovers (Pluvialis apricaria), we can observe a similar (albeit much small scale) version of the plover migration. Overwintering populations migrate to the northern Spain August - November, and spend the summer in the UK.
